author: Freya Noble For Daily Mail Australia
title: Witnesses saw plane crash into Melbourne Essendon Airport | Daily Mail Online
text: Share this article Share Motorists on the nearby Tullamarine freeway have posted videos and pictures of black smoke pouring out from the side of the DFO building. The Tullamarine and Calder freeways remain closed as firefighters work at the crash scene. Premier Daniel Andrews described the crash as 'the worst civil aviation accident in 30 years' saying 'a number of people' had died in the tragedy. 'Our thoughts, prayers, best wishes and support to all of those who have been caught up in this,' he said on Tuesday afternoon. Victoria Ambulance said 'it looks like nobody survived the crash'. Authorities have not been able to confirm any injuries or fatalities at this stage 'There is constant explosions going off, there is black smoke billowing into the sky,' one witness said 'I saw a ball of flames,' one terrified onlooker said A wheel from the plane ended up on the Tullamarine Freeway (pictured) After the crash a wheel from the plane ended up on the Tullamarine Freeway, closing the road in both directions and delaying emergency services. VicRoads warned commuters to avoid the area and expect heavy delays on all detours. Firefighters hosed down the side of the DFO building and the charred remains of the plane. ABC radio caller Jason was in a taxi when he looked out the window and saw what he thought was a twin-propeller plane. Firefighters are hosing down the side of the DFO building The plane left Essendon Airport with five people on board about 9am before crashing into the DFO building a short time later 'I saw this plane coming in really low and fast. It went just behind the barriers so I couldn't see the impact but when it hit the building there was a massive fireball,' he told ABC 774. 'I could feel the heat through the window of the taxi, and then a wheel, it looked like a plane wheel, bounced on the road and hit the front of the taxi as we were driving along. 'We kept driving and there was big fireball behind us.' Share or comment on this article 325
